%S A395795 1,4,6,15,35,55,91,119,209,253,319,403,481,533,559,799,901,1003,1037,
%T A395795 1139,1349,1387,1501,1577,1691,2231,2323,2369,2461,2507,2599,3683,
%U A395795 3799,3973,4031,4321,4379,4553,5053,5177,5363,5549,5611,5921,5983,7289,7363,7807,8251
%N A395795 Lexicographically earliest sequence of non-prime terms such that (a) for all k>=0, a(k) shares a factor with exactly k other terms, and (b) for all k >= 1, a(k) is divisible by a prime which does not divide any earlier term.
%C A395795 The terms are created by considering the earliest term a(k) that does not yet share a factor with k other terms, and then adding a new term a(n) which is the product of the largest prime p in a(k) with the n-th prime. New terms are added containing p as one of the factors until k terms exist that share a factor with a(k).
%H A395795 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A395795/b395795.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..10000</a>
%e A395795 a(0) = 1, as 1 shares zero factors with any other terms.
%e A395795 a(1) = 4, the first non-prime term. As this is even there can only be one more even term.
%e A395795 a(2) = 6. This shares a factor with a(1) = 4, and so satisfies a(1) sharing a factor with one other term. This is the last even term. Note that 6 = 2*3, so it equals the largest prime in a(1), the earliest term not yet sharing with one other factor, multiplied by the 2nd prime.
%e A395795 a(3) = 15. Note 15 = 3*5, so it equals the largest prime in a(2), the next earliest term not yet sharing with two other factors, multiplied by the 3rd prime. This satisfies a(2) sharing a factor with two other terms; it is the last term divisible by 3. A seemingly viable non-prime odd term is 9 = 3*3, but then a(2) would share factors with two terms so no further terms could contain 2 or 3 as factors, but that would violate the condition that a(3) = 9 needs to share a factor with three other terms. This restriction is true for all subsequent prime powers beyond 4.
%e A395795 a(4) = 35. Note 35 = 5*7, so it equals the largest prime in a(3), the next earliest term not yet sharing with three other factors, multiplied by the 4th prime.
%e A395795 a(5) = 55. Note 55 = 5*11, so it equals the largest prime in a(3), the next earliest term not yet sharing with three other factors, multiplied by the 5th prime. This satisfies a(3) sharing a factor with three other terms; it is the last term divisible by 5.
%e A395795 a(6) = 91. Note 91 = 7*13, so it equals the largest prime in a(4), the next earliest term not yet sharing with four other factors, multiplied by the 6th prime.
%Y A395795 Cf. A395360, A392373, A002808, A006881.
%K A395795 nonn,new
%O A395795 0,2
